{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Rows with missing required fields are rejected and appear in the dead-letter queue with the original row number.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: CSV parser must preserve row index, validator must reject, and DLQ writer must persist the same index/payload. Unit tests on validator alone can miss row-number propagation bugs. Integration-Brake: no real OS/network/subprocess required if DLQ is replaced with an in-process fake sink; no AI/ML dependency; no multi-agent chain. Rejection-Gate: rejected System because behavior text does not require real queue infrastructure, only that rejected rows and row numbers are emitted correctly.","test_description":"Run pipeline components together (parser + validator + DLQ adapter) against a fixture CSV with missing required fields; use an in-process fake DLQ collector and assert each rejected record includes the original CSV row number and raw row content.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The transformation correctly converts date strings in multiple formats (ISO 8601, US, European) to a single canonical format.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure transformation logic at one function/object boundary. Real failures are parsing/normalization algorithm mistakes, reproducible with direct inputs and expected outputs. No module handoff is required to expose the bug.","test_description":"Table-driven unit test for date-normalization function with ISO 8601, US (MM/DD/YYYY), and European (DD/MM/YYYY) inputs (plus edge dates), asserting exact canonical output and explicit failures for ambiguous/invalid dates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure depends on real runtime characteristics (process memory growth, GC behavior, wall-clock throughput under large input), which mocks often hide. REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE both point above Integration because in-process fakes for storage/network can mask buffering/backpressure behavior that causes OOM/timeouts.","test_description":"System performance test that runs the actual pipeline process on a 500k-row CSV with production-like config, measures end-to-end elapsed time against timeout, and monitors peak RSS to ensure no OOM and bounded memory usage.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior is retry orchestration across modules (S3 client adapter + retry policy + batch controller). A deterministic stub that returns 503 then success can expose real policy/state bugs. Integration-Brake: (a) real network not strictly required for this failure mode, so not forced to System; (b) no AI/ML output dependency; (c) no multi-agent chain. Rejection-Gate: rejected System because behavior text focuses on retry/backoff decisioning, which is verifiable with controlled responses and clock control.","test_description":"Integration test wiring batch processor with S3 adapter stub that returns 503 for first N attempts then success; use fake clock/sleeper to assert exponential backoff intervals and verify batch continues and completes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to PostgreSQL are not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is state handoff across pipeline progress tracking and DB write semantics (idempotency/upsert/checkpoint). This needs multiple modules plus a real local DB transaction model; unit fakes can miss duplicate-write races/constraint behavior. Integration-Brake: no mandatory external OS/network/subprocess beyond local DB interaction; no AI dependency; no multi-agent chain. Rejection-Gate: rejected System because behavior does not require OS-level restart mechanics specifically; restart can be simulated by reinitializing pipeline against persisted state.","test_description":"Integration test with local PostgreSQL: process part of a batch, simulate restart by creating a new pipeline instance with persisted checkpoint/state, continue processing, then assert row uniqueness (primary key or dedupe key) and exact final row count with no duplicates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
